Moral dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the U.S. government represents an enormous bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses have continued to balloon in light of falling housing prices.
Now that the government is fully guaranteeing Fannie and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to foot the bill for whatever remains uncovered by the inadequate funds of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the openly capitalist country of the world?
Do the time-honored principles of capitalism not include the idea that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie now have to accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers have to bear the brunt of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly delineated.
But they are not.
It is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers anything in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that could bring the financial sector, and thus the world economy, to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify, it does not follow that they do not exist.
Moreover, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee of the U.S. government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a bailout by the U.S. government could undermine confidence in government securities and, because they are associated with these, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend beyond the U.S. economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative booms and busts in asset values, bringing questions of trust as well as fairness into the equation.
Also in many other countries, similar booms in the housing sector are coming to an end, and they may face the same challenges—and the same moral dilemmas—as the U.S. economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are also subject to this.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of five between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The S&P BSE Sensex in India rose by a factor of five in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost one-third of its value.
Similar booms and crashes of stock markets have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they continued, the booms preceding these crashes overheated these economies.
Now that the boom has turned into a bust, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to prop up the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when help is absent as markets collapse.
The reactions of people to these events depend on their emotions and sense of justice.
The described boom and bust cycles have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Who invested in the stock market or the housing market fared well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will assess the fairness of these results based on what they were told and the implicit promises they drew from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets they invested their money in?
Did everything really match the truth?
There is unfortunately no way to find out.
Policy can only react generally and not address each case individually.
We know that recent economic growth in many countries has been spectacular.
But were the investments in their markets overpriced?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that the boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, while there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not scraping by at the poverty line.
However, we cannot conclude from this that all their losses should be borne without limitation.
The nagging problem concerns "trust and fidelity."
Economies flourish only when "trust and fidelity" prevail.
The current situation, where speculative booms have driven the global economy—and now, after their collapse, are pushing it into recession—suggests that those who promoted certain capital investments did so in violation of trust and fidelity.
Take the investors who purchased bonds from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to come to their aid in times of need, it established a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, has never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is discovering the capitalism and its power to transform economies.
The capitalism relies on trust and fidelity.
An unfairly treated situation can be fatal for economic growth, as it means that people will lose trust in companies and thus be less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Is such a result preferable to a bailout from a moral standpoint?
